work_exp:
[u"COO
Hi-Tech Manufacturing
January 2014 to January 2016
Lead operations and strategic direction while upgrading quality systems and integrating acquisitions. Full responsibility for bottom line
performance including product and process development, capital expenditures, supply chain management, and customer retention across multiple factories allowing the CEO to focus on acquisitions. Established a baseline for diversification both organically and through
acquisitions, and broadened product offering and manufacturing capabilities to support future growth.
• Led NPI launch for medical device and aerospace manufacture including achieving ISO14385 and AS9100 certifications while bring all manufacturing and assembly operations within the guidelines of FDA GMP;
• Reduced manufacturing costs of existing products at established North American operations, while accelerating NPI cycle;
• Planned, managed and completed the integration of acquisitions into Hi-Tech's culture, controls, KPIs, and financial systems
while expanding cash flow for the organization as a whole;
• Integrated supply chain partnerships to reduce inventory, carrying costs, and improve delivery. Went from 2.2 to 3.8 turns
overall while increasing OTD metrics by lowering raw and WIP inventories and properly balancing finished goods;
• Doubled the capacity and increased production output by more than 65% in the Dongguan, China facility, while reducing
internal DPPM by half and eliminating customer returns;
• Directed accelerated product and process development for exotic material aerospace fittings to offset declining sales during the slump in the oil and gas market.", u'PRESIDENT
Kyocera Tycom Corporation
January 2009 to January 2014
Complete P&L responsibility for this cutting tool manufacturing company with multiple manufacturing and resharpening/service/sales
facilities worldwide. Formulate the corporate vision and strategic direction, lead the strategic planning process, support all growth
strategies, oversee major financial management and new product development initiatives, provide strategic guidance on operations,
direct capital creation efforts, and approve capital projects.
• Grew EBITDA from 1.5% to over 12% in a commodity manufacturing operation by optimizing supply chain and streamlining
operations, while increasing revenue by 3% per year;
• Implemented 6-Sigma and lean Perfect 5S programs throughout the enterprise establishing a culture of data driven continual
improvement that continues to this day;
• Assembled, mentored and handed the operations off to a world class management team when they were ready to take the reins
ensuring ~~~~~~~~~ operational success;
• Developed and integrated an Hourly Efficiency (HE) metric and drove a 65% increase over the 5 years as President though a combination of targeted growth strategies, capital upgrades, 6-Sigma directed projects, distributed financial accountability,
reduced product cycle times, and incentivized associate continual improvement involvement;
• Rationalized financial and KPI systems within the Kyocera framework laying the groundwork for meaningful benchmarking
and best practices adaptation with the $16B larger Kyocera family.', u'VP-OPERATIONS
Kyocera Tycom Corporation
January 2001 to January 2009
Lead operations direction. Accountable for cost, quality and delivery of all products and resharpening services the company provided
worldwide. Integrated production operations within the Kyocera manufacturing family
• Directed automation projects which resulted in two processes that became patented and established dominance in the resharpening services market in North America while reducing DPPM levels by 35% and costs by 60%;
• Led Kyocera America corporate efforts at consolidating supply base and reducing costs;
• Reduced manufacturing costs by 45% over two years by streamlining labor and raw material content while and spreading
fixed cost base;
• Restructured operations in wake of 2001 electronic market collapse;
• Started operations in China and Japan as customer base moved to region, and;
• Developed and integrated captive strategic supply base in India increasing manufacturing margins by 4.5% and increasing
capacity by 30% without capital investment.', u'DIRECTOR of OPERATIONS
Kyocera Tycom Corporation
January 1997 to January 2001
Lead operations direction. Accountable for cost, quality and delivery of all products and resharpening services the company provided
worldwide.
• Established manufacturing, sales and service operations in the US and 8 other countries worldwide;
• Took the lead role in acquisition of Precision Carbide;
• Lead in sale of Tycom to Kyocera from Private Equity to Strategic buyer;
• Used KPI systems to drive up machine utilization and down machining cycle time which allowed the delay of over $3M in capital equipment during a time of hyper-growth;
• Used a combination of consigned inventories and JIT delivery systems to maintain raw material inventories despite an almost
3X increase in production output.
• Developed dental tool product line and process to allow for diversification outside cutting tools.', u'ENGINEERING & QUALITY MANAGER
Kyocera Tycom Corporation
January 1991 to January 1997
Established and integrated quality and engineering systems to allow the company to prosper during hyper growth years
• Integrated AOI inspection systems for final product verification;
• Combined developed automated handling systems to AOI inspection and final packaging to eliminate tool handling damage;
• Established on-floor SPC monitoring system to reduce defects and ensure shop floor operators took responsibility for product
quality.']
